{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 16:09:25.437640", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnostic report — Clos (fat-tree) EBGP fabric\\nDate: (current capture)\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Overall network health: GOOD. Control-plane (BGP) and data-plane checks show no reachability loss between hosts; all expected /24 host prefixes are present in BGP/RIBs across the fabric. No interfaces are administratively down and I/O error counters are zero.\\n- No outages or routing blackholes detected. BGP sessions are established and routes are being exchanged; traffic is forwarding and host-to-host pings report 0% loss.\\n- Observations & minor notes: ECMP / multipath behavior is visible for inter-pod prefixes (multiple next-hops shown). Certain inter-router links and leaf-to-host links show high packet counters consistent with the observed traffic patterns (traffic concentration), not with errors.\\n\\nWhat I checked (tools / data)\\n- End-to-end reachability (ping matrix): cross-host reachability test completed (sample results returned).\\n- Per-host network configuration (ifconfig / ip addr / ip route) for:\\n  - Hosts: pc_0_0, pc_0_1\\n  - Routers: leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, super_spine_router_0\\n- FRR BGP tables and IP routing tables (frr_show_ip_route / BGP table outputs) on the routers.\\n\\nDetailed findings\\n\\n1) Data-plane (host reachability)\\n- Ping matrix summary: All tested host pairs succeeded with 0% packet loss. Example RTTs:\\n  - pc_0_0 → pc_1_0: 0% loss, avg RTT ~3.8 ms\\n  - pc_0_1 → pc_0_0: 0% loss, avg RTT ~2.25 ms\\n- Host interfaces and routes:\\n  - pc_0_0: 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1 (leaf_router_0_0)\\n  - pc_0_1: 10.0.1.2/24, default via 10.0.1.1 (leaf_router_0_1)\\n- No packet drops or interface errors reported on hosts (RX/TX error counters 0).\\n\\n2) Control-plane (BGP / routing)\\n- BGP sessions are up and prefixes are being exchanged across AS boundaries.\\n- Each leaf advertises its directly connected /24 and those prefixes appear in the BGP tables of spine and super-spine routers.\\n  - leaf_router_0_0: 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected and present in its BGP table.\\n  - leaf_router_0_1: 10.0.1.0/24 is directly connected and present.\\n- Super-spine and spine routers have learned all 10.0.x.0/24 and 10.1.x.0/24 prefixes; best-paths and multiple alternative paths are visible (ECMP/multipath across spines/super-spine). Example:\\n  - spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1 show multiple next-hops for the 10.1.* prefixes (multiple AS-paths/next-hops), indicating expected multi-homing/ECMP to the super-spine set.\\n- No signs of route suppression, damping, or RIB failures in the provided BGP outputs.\\n\\n3) Interface-level and traffic observations\\n- All router interfaces are UP/LOWER_UP with no RX/TX error counters.\\n- High packet counters appear on the following interfaces (consistent with host traffic flows):\\n  - leaf_router_0_0:\\n    - eth4 (10.0.0.1) — RX 52,629 / TX 27 (host → leaf traffic observed)\\n    - eth1 — TX 52,635 (forwarded upstream)\\n  - leaf_router_0_1:\\n    - eth4 (10.0.1.1) — TX 52,460 / RX 15 (host-facing stats show expected asymmetry)\\n    - eth1 — RX 52,476 (traffic between leaf and spine)\\n  - spine_router_0_1:\\n    - eth2 — RX 52,601 (heavy upstream traffic)\\n    - eth3 — TX 52,599\\n- The packet flows and counters are consistent end-to-end (PCs transmit; leaves receive and forward to spines; spines show corresponding counters). There are no drops/errors reported.\\n\\n4) Consistency with topology / addressing\\n- Inter-router point-to-point links use /31s in 172.16.0.0/16 as described; assigned addresses are present and consistent across routers (e.g., leaf_router_0_0 eth0 172.16.0.33/31, spine_router_0_0 eth2 172.16.0.32/31, super_spine eth0 172.16.0.0/31, etc.).\\n- EBGP AS assignments seen in BGP outputs correspond to the multi-AS layout in the description (leaves 65200 / 65201, spines 65100 / 65101, super-spine 65000).\\n\\nAnomalies / faults\\n- No critical anomalies detected. Specifically:\\n  - No packet loss between hosts (0% loss in pings performed).\\n  - All expected host subnets (10.0.0.0/24, 10.0.1.0/24, 10.1.x.0/24) are present in BGP tables across the fabric.\\n  - No interface-level errors (RX/TX errors = 0).\\n  - BGP tables show active route entries and multiple valid paths where expected (ECMP).\\n- Minor observations (not failures):\\n  - Multipath/ECMP is in effect for many inter-pod prefixes. This is expected in Clos fabrics but may show different \"best path\" choices on different routers depending on AS-path / next-hop selection (observed differences in preferred next-hops between spines).\\n  - Some interfaces show very large transmit or receive counters (50k+ packets). This is a traffic volume observation — not an error — but useful to note for capacity/monitoring.\\n\\nLocalization summary (nodes checked and status)\\n- Hosts:\\n  - pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) — reachable, no errors.\\n  - pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2) — reachable, no errors.\\n- Leaves:\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 — interfaces UP, BGP routes present, local /24 advertised.\\n  - leaf_router_0_1 — interfaces UP, BGP routes present, local /24 advertised.\\n- Spines:\\n  - spine_router_0_0 — interfaces UP, BGP learned routes present.\\n  - spine_router_0_1 — interfaces UP, BGP learned routes present.\\n- Super-spine:\\n  - super_spine_router_0 — interfaces UP, BGP learned routes present.\\n- Conclusion: No faulty devices identified.\\n\\nProbable root cause(s)\\n- Because no outage or error signatures were observed, there is no root-cause of failure to identify. All forwarding and BGP announcements are operating as expected. The observed behavior (ECMP, different best next-hops on some routers) matches normal EBGP/AS-path selection behavior in a multi-AS Clos topology.\\n\\nKey evidence (pointer to concrete outputs)\\n- Reachability: ping matrix — 0% loss between tested hosts.\\n- BGP/routing: FRR BGP tables and show ip route show:\\n  - Each leaf has its /24 locally connected and the prefix is visible in spine and super-spine BGP tables.\\n  - Spines/super-spine show multiple next-hops for some prefixes (ECMP), and selected best paths are visible in the RIB.\\n- Interface counters: ifconfig outputs show heavy packet counts on leaf<->spine and leaf<->host interfaces, aligned with traffic.\\n\\nIf you want next steps (not requested now)\\n- I can run targeted BGP neighbor/state checks, show ip bgp neighbors for adjacency states, run traceroutes between specific hosts to show hop-by-hop forwarding, or collect live interface byte counters over time to confirm steady-state traffic patterns. (I will not propose or apply mitigation actions unless you ask.)\\n\\nBottom line\\n- Fabric appears healthy: control-plane stable, data-plane forwarding verified, no packet loss, and all expected prefixes distributed. No faulty router or link was found in the captured data., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='f2525870-01e1-4407-b0f5-31947b11392c'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
